Dear Apple Support,

I am writing to bring to your attention an issue I have encountered with the headphones I purchased from Apple in March 2024. Approximately three months after purchasing the product, I started experiencing problems with the right (R) side, where the sound began cutting out. As a result, I took the headphones to the KVK service center in early August. The service center informed me that the right side was missing a speaker grill, something I was unaware of since the day I bought the product.

The KVK service refused to cover this issue under warranty and demanded a fee for the repair. Additionally, the staff’s behavior was quite rude and unprofessional. Considering that the product is still under warranty and has only been used for five months, I believe this issue is a manufacturing defect rather than something caused by user error.

I kindly request that my headphones be reviewed under warranty and that the necessary repairs or replacements be made free of charge. As a loyal Apple customer, I expect a resolution that reflects the quality and service Apple is known for.

Thank you for your attention to this matter. I look forward to your prompt assistance.

Best regards,

alt: A series of photos depict recycled iPhone parts in close up, concluding with a shot of all the parts together in a geometric pattern.
caption:
Commissioned by Apple. When you recycle an iPhone, even the smallest pieces have a big role to play.

Battery: Using a mass balance allocation, 56 percent of all cobalt and 24 percent of all lithium shipped in Apple batteries in 2023 came from recycled sources.

Speaker: Made with recycled rare-earth elements.

Aluminum Frame: In 2023, 71 percent of the aluminum shipped to customers came from recycled sources. 
  
Camera and Main Logic Board: From just one metric ton of iPhone main logic boards, flexes and camera modules, we’re capable of recovering the same amount of gold and copper as found in more than 2000 metric tons of mined rock.

Head into your nearest Apple store to recycle iPhones you’re no longer using or go to Apple.com/recycle to learn more.

#ShotoniPhone by Todd M. @toddmclellan.

Additional editing software used.

latestComments/1/text: Did you know that cobalt is a mineral used for batteries in electric cars, computers, and mobile phones? More than 70 percent of the world’s cobalt is produced in the Democratic Republic of the Congo, and a lot of if comes from artisanal mines. These small mines are often dangerous as the mining and refining processes are often labour intensive and associated with a variety of health problems. This can be as a result of accidents, overexertion, exposure to toxic chemicals and gases, and violence. These miners, known locally as creseurs, are economically reliant on these mines but still only make less than 10USD per day
